{"key":"processedPost-13181816","value":{"id":13181816,"first":13181182,"last":13182054,"when":1284258246,"utime":"09/12/10 05:24 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>Tangich said:</b><br />Yeah, that's why I said, find the specimen you like and clone it! 1% of the work with isolation, and often even better results.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Apparently you're not aware that there can be many active strains in a single fruit.&nbsp; Cloning is no guarantee of an isolate.&nbsp; Those of us who isolate cubensis generally do it to find the best of the best.&nbsp; It's not necessary of course, but it's simply taking the hobby to the next level, which isn't for everyone.<br /><br />To the original poster, P cubensis generally grows very well from multispore inoculation.&nbsp; The many strains that form generally join into a coherent organism by fruiting time.&nbsp; Often, there will be several strains fruiting at once, as can easily be seen in grows where fruits are very different in appearance from each other.&nbsp; However, it's rare to use multispore inoculation and come up with a bunk strain that doesn't fruit at all.<br />RR","title":"Re: Is it evil that I don't isolate?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}